T1  - The Relationship Between Environmental Commitment and Managerial Perceptions of Stakeholder Importance
AU  - Henriques, Irene
AU  - Sadorsky, Perry
Y1  - 1999/02/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256876
DO  - 10.5465/256876
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 87
EP  - 99
VL  - 42
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Do firms committed to stewardship of the natural environment differ from less environmentally committed firms in their perceptions of the relative importance of different stakeholders in influencing their environmental practices? Using cluster analysis on six responses to questions describing a firm's practices, we classified 400 firms into four environmental profiles: reactive, defensive, accommodative, and proactive. Results indicate that firms with more proactive profiles do differ from less environmentally committed firms in their perceptions of the relative importance of different stakeholders.
AB  - Do firms committed to stewardship of the natural environment differ from less environmentally committed firms in their perceptions of the relative importance of different stakeholders in influencing their environmental practices? Using cluster analysis on six responses to questions describing a firm's practices, we classified 400 firms into four environmental profiles: reactive, defensive, accommodative, and proactive. Results indicate that firms with more proactive profiles do differ from less environmentally committed firms in their perceptions of the relative importance of different stakeholders.
